STOA NOTES:

I've applied The Law of Threes as a top-down organizational model. This separates *concepts* into two categories: quantifiable, and not. The vast majority of Physical Wealth is quantifiable with science. At least really, really good Educated Guesses, like the 'value' of a nation's Tantalum deposits. When everything else is stripped away, the main Invention of the PET, that is, the Patriarchal, Exploitative Technocracy (the Ruling Class since the dawn of recorded history), is Money. Like all the BEATs (best active/reactive technology, that is, combines the best aspects of an emergent phenomenon and the best engineered utility) of Humanity's Heart, Money is *both* an Emergent and Engineered Resource. The *idea* of value now has value. This happened around the time we 'invented' number systems and alphabets. 

I don't talk about the Heart. The Heart is a Secondary Value, the 'border' between the Soul and the Mind. I am a rational humanist. I do not believe, by definition, that anything *can* be Supernatural. The Soul is a metaphor, and always has been, perhaps The Best Metaphor. The Soul is the metaphor for the Total State of Being. In encompasses the Body's physical state and the Mind's mental state, but is a completely emergent property like both. Which is why I need a STOA. These three things have defined all of human history: Control of the Physical, Control of the Mental, and Control of the Spiritual. When we surrender control, we give power to the PET, or as I call it colloquially, The Faustocracy. These are the people who have all the information available, saw the physical rewards, saw the price in suffering, and decided That's Fair. The Analogue I use is the farmer who 'owns' his field in the late paleolithic. His family has lived there since the dawn of time, so it is *his* land. There are other owners, and if you leave each other alone, nothing happens. The problem comes when you have more Kids than owners. The Kids Need Something To Do (otherwise they break stuff), so the Farmer offers them Food in exchange for Labor. The farmer gets more food than he can eat, and gives some to his neighbor for some chickens. The Chickens Lay more eggs than the farmer can ever eat, so he trades those...  etc, etc. The complexity has become unmanageable, so he starts Writing Things Down. He "Invents" Money. The Farmer is So Proud of himself, and has Helped So Many Kids, that he thinks he, *maybe*, should have a bigger house than the other Farmers. The Age of Money is born, the Old Ways die, and the Farmer and the Kids (who are older and wiser now, but Not As Wise as The Farmer), have a lot of down time as they work together to *automate* labor. So they sit around and Talk to Each Other. The Farmer finds out The Kids aren't Always Happy not having as much Food as the Farmer, and ask for small farms of their own. The only way to do that, now that he's *surrounded* by neighbors, is to give them a Piece of The Farm. The Farmer fights *tooth and nail* for every piece, meanwhile the Kids are Literally Suffering before his very eyes. The Farmer "invents" Semantics, Mathematics, and Propaganda. He "invents" *two things* to *define* the Farm and The Debate, and *one thing* to *convince* the Kids that He Is Right, outside of The Debate. He Has The Gold, So He Makes The Rules. That's why he thinks he only needs one layer of defenses, which for him is Propaganda, but for the Kids is Rhetoric. Because the Kids aren't just debating the Farmer, they are debating *each other* and don't want anyone's feelings to get hurt. At some point, the Debate agrees that The Kids should all own The Kids Part, and The Farmer will own the Farmer Part. Now it's a War of Attrition with our own nature. The last three things that The Farmer "invented" to measure his Farm and Make The Rules are Free-Market Capitalism and Western Democracy. The Kids, at the same time, came up with Communism, Socialism, and Anarchism: "Everybody owns The Farm," "Nobody owns The Farm," and "Maybe we should Kill The Farmer." Note the Anarchist does not say "Kill The Farmer and Our Problems Are Solved." (Although, some of her followers do.) She says, "Killing The Farmer is an Option We Should Talk About." The Three Kids become the sub-users of the Faustocracy. They Are Convinced that if they just come up with One Good Idea, the Farmer will give All Kids a bigger part of the Farm. This arrangement is *actively encouraged* by the Farmer, who has been listening the whole time. This Debate takes Twelve Thousand Years and only ends when The Anarchist writes up a list of Formal Grievances about how The Farmer Is Wrong about the Value he is giving Labor. This prompts a Five Hundred Year Discussion on the meaning of Right and Wrong. This culminates in a competition to see who can Build The Best Plow, The Farmer, with his history of farming in his family, or The Kids, who have been farming and talking all this time? The Farmer and The Kids are now so *entrenched* in The Debate for More Land, they don't even notice The Rain Has Stopped. When The Anarchist points this out, The Other Boss Kids and The Farmer *call her insane* and *insist* the fact that it's not raining every morning and The Farm Is Slowly Dying is just Part of The Weather. When she finally says The Fact, that The Rain Came Because it went into the ground and into the plants, then enough came back *out* of the ground and the plants to Make More Rain. She points out the fact that They Need More Plants because The Farmer got Married and there's A Lot More Kids, and says The Rain Wont Come Back until they stop fucking so much. They then kick her off the Farm and she goes back to the Old Ways, hunting and gathering. She thinks The Farm will Kill Them All, and they think The Wilderness Will Kill Her. And for some reason, *everyone is fine with that*.

That's where we are today. The Farmer and His Wife, who was a Kid from Another Farm, still 'own' the Big Part of the Farm. The Kids are trying to feed as many of themselves as they can while also feeding the Farmer and His Wife, who have Grown Old and Fat, while letting their excess Food Rot In The Silo. There's also a Big Machine on the Farm that is the result of all those Automation Debates. It *mostly* does *okay* counting the Food and putting it in the silo. It makes a lot of noise and smoke, constantly leaks fuel, needs more and more Water to not fuck itself Every Day, and is delicately maintained by Some Of The Kids and a roaming Farmer who only visits when The Kids are asleep. The Machine is a BEAT, the most optimized combination of emergent concepts and engineered ideals. Except this BEAT is also a lie maintained by the Farmer, who's been sneaking out to the Machine every night to Fuck With It to cheat the Kids.

